  "prompt": "How long does it take for teeth to relapse (move) after a broken retainer?",
  "response": "The time it takes for teeth to relapse (move out of alignment) after a broken retainer varies depending on several factors, including the individual\u2019s age, the original orthodontic treatment, how long the retainer was worn, and the natural tendency of the teeth to shift. However, teeth can begin to move within **days to weeks** after the retainer is no longer in use.\n\n### Key Factors Influencing Relapse:\n1. **Time Since Orthodontic Treatment**: If the retainer broke shortly after braces were removed, teeth are more likely to shift quickly. The first 6-12 months after treatment are critical for maintaining alignment.\n\n2. **Natural Stability of Teeth**: Some people\u2019s teeth are inherently more stable, while others are prone to shifting due to factors like gum health, jaw growth, or tongue pressure.\n\n3. **Duration Without a Retainer**: The longer you go without a retainer, the greater the chance of relapse. Even small shifts can become noticeable over time.\n\n4. **Type of Retainer**: If you had a fixed (permanent) retainer, the teeth it held in place may shift more quickly if it breaks compared to a removable retainer.\n\n5. **Age**: Younger individuals, especially those in their late teens or early twenties, may experience faster relapse because their jaws are still developing.\n\n### What to Do If Your Retainer Breaks:\n- **Contact Your Orthodontist**: Schedule an appointment as soon as possible to replace or repair the retainer. Some orthodontists can provide a temporary solution if needed.\n- **Monitor Your Teeth**: Keep an eye on any noticeable shifts and inform your orthodontist.\n- **Wear Any Remaining Retainers**: If you have a backup retainer or a retainer for the opposite arch, continue wearing it to minimize movement.\n\n### Preventing Relapse:\n- Always follow your orthodontist\u2019s instructions for retainer use, which typically involves wearing it full-time initially and then gradually transitioning to nighttime wear.\n- If you suspect your retainer is broken or lost, act quickly to address the issue.\n\nIn summary, teeth can start moving within **days to weeks** after a retainer breaks, so prompt action is essential to maintain your smile\u2019s alignment.",
